  "prompt": "Why is sodium hydrogen carbonate soluble in water?",
  "response": "Sodium hydrogen carbonate (NaHCO\u2083), commonly known as baking soda, is soluble in water due to several factors related to its chemical structure and interactions with water molecules.\n\n1. **Ionic Nature**: NaHCO\u2083 is an ionic compound, which means it is composed of positively charged sodium ions (Na\u207a) and negatively charged hydrogen carbonate ions (HCO\u2083\u207b). Ionic compounds generally dissolve well in polar solvents like water because the positive and negative parts of the water molecule (H\u2082O) can interact with the ions.\n\n2. **Hydration Energy**: When NaHCO\u2083 dissolves in water, the water molecules surround and stabilize the sodium and hydrogen carbonate ions through ion-dipole interactions. This process, known as hydration, releases energy that helps to overcome the lattice energy of the solid crystalline structure of NaHCO\u2083.\n\n3. **Polar Solvent**: Water is a highly polar solvent, and due to its polarity, it can effectively dissolve ionic compounds. The negatively charged oxygen atoms in water molecules attract the positively charged sodium ions, and the positively charged hydrogen atoms in water molecules attract the negatively charged hydrogen carbonate ions.\n\n4. **Weak Electrostatic Forces**: The ions in NaHCO\u2083 are held together by ionic bonds, but these bonds are relatively weak compared to covalent bonds. In water, the weak electrostatic forces can be easily overcome by the strong ion-dipole interactions with water molecules.\n\n5. **Chemical Equilibrium**: The dissolution of NaHCO\u2083 in water can lead to the formation of bicarbonate (HCO\u2083\u207b) and carbonate (CO\u2083\u00b2\u207b) ions, with equilibrium favoring solubilized forms that promote the continuous dissolution of sodium hydrogen carbonate.\n\nDue to these reasons, NaHCO\u2083 is quite soluble in water, making it versatile for various applications ranging from cooking to medical uses as an antacid.",
